Class DefaultObjectWrapper.ExtendableBuilder<ProductT extends DefaultObjectWrapper,SelfT extends DefaultObjectWrapper.ExtendableBuilder<ProductT,SelfT>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.apache.freemarker.core.model.impl.DefaultObjectWrapper.ExtendableBuilder<ProductT,SelfT>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Cloneable, CommonBuilder<ProductT>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DefaultObjectWrapper.Builder, RestrictedObjectWrapper.ExtendableBuilder
    Enclosing class:
    DefaultObjectWrapper

    protected abstract static class DefaultObjectWrapper.ExtendableBuilder<ProductT extends DefaultObjectWrapper,SelfT extends DefaultObjectWrapper.ExtendableBuilder<ProductT,SelfT>>
extends Object
implements CommonBuilder<ProductT>, Cloneable
    You will not use this abstract class directly, but concrete subclasses like DefaultObjectWrapper.Builder, unless you are developing a builder for a custom DefaultObjectWrapper subclass. In that case, note that overriding the equals(java.lang.Object) and hashCode() is important, as these objects are used as ObjectWrapper singleton lookup keys.

    • Constructor Detail

      • ExtendableBuilder

        protected ExtendableBuilder(Version incompatibleImprovements,
                            boolean isIncompImprsAlreadyNormalized)
        Parameters:
        incompatibleImprovements - Sets which of the non-backward-compatible improvements should be enabled. Not null. This version number is the same as the FreeMarker version number with which the improvements were implemented.

        For new projects, it's recommended to set this to the FreeMarker version that's used during the development. For released products that are still actively developed it's a low risk change to increase the 3rd version number further as FreeMarker is updated, but of course you should always check the list of effects below. Increasing the 2nd or 1st version number possibly mean substantial changes with higher risk of breaking the application, but again, see the list of effects below.

        The reason it's separate from Configuration.getIncompatibleImprovements() is that ObjectWrapper objects are sometimes shared among multiple Configuration-s, so the two version numbers are technically independent. But it's recommended to keep those two version numbers the same.

        The changes enabled by incompatibleImprovements are:

        • 3.0.0: No changes; this is the starting point, the version used in older projects.

        Note that the version will be normalized to the lowest version where the same incompatible DefaultObjectWrapper improvements were already present, so getIncompatibleImprovements() might returns a lower version than what you have specified.

        isIncompImprsAlreadyNormalized - Tells if the incompatibleImprovements parameter contains an already normalized value. This parameter meant to be true when the class that extends DefaultObjectWrapper needs to add additional breaking versions over those of DefaultObjectWrapper. Thus, if this parameter is true, the versions where DefaultObjectWrapper had breaking changes must be already factored into the incompatibleImprovements parameter value, as no more normalization will happen. (You can use DefaultObjectWrapper.normalizeIncompatibleImprovementsVersion(Version) to discover those.)

      • cloneForCacheKey

        protected SelfT cloneForCacheKey()
        If the builder is used as a cache key, this is used to clone it before it's stored in the cache as a key, so that further changes in the original builder won't change the key (aliasing). It calls Object.clone() internally, so all fields are automatically copied, but it will also individually clone field values that are both mutable and has a content-based equals method (deep cloning).

        If you extend DefaultObjectWrapper.ExtendableBuilder with new fields with mutable values that have a content-based equals method, and you will also cache product instances, you need to clone those values manually to prevent aliasing problems, so don't forget to override this method!

        See Also:
        equals(Object), hashCode()

      • setOuterIdentity

        public void setOuterIdentity(ObjectWrapper outerIdentity)
        When wrapping an object, the DefaultObjectWrapper commonly needs to wrap "sub-objects", for example each element in a wrapped collection. Normally it wraps these objects using itself. However, this makes it difficult to delegate to a DefaultObjectWrapper as part of a custom aggregate ObjectWrapper. This method lets you set the ObjectWrapper which will be used to wrap the sub-objects.
        Parameters:
        outerIdentity - the aggregate ObjectWrapper, or null if we will use the object created by this builder.

      • isStrict

      • setStrict

        public void setStrict(boolean strict)
        Specifies if an attempt to read a bean property that doesn't exist in the wrapped object should throw an InvalidPropertyException.

        If this property is false (the default) then an attempt to read a missing bean property is the same as reading an existing bean property whose value is null. The template can't tell the difference, and thus always can use ?default('something') and ?exists and similar built-ins to handle the situation.

        If this property is true then an attempt to read a bean propertly in the template (like myBean.aProperty) that doesn't exist in the bean object (as opposed to just holding null value) will cause InvalidPropertyException, which can't be suppressed in the template (not even with myBean.noSuchProperty?default('something')). This way ?default('something') and ?exists and similar built-ins can be used to handle existing properties whose value is null, without the risk of hiding typos in the property names. Typos will always cause error. But mind you, it goes against the basic approach of FreeMarker, so use this feature only if you really know what you are doing.

      • getExtensions

        public List<? extends DefaultObjectWrapperExtension> getExtensions()
        Extensions are used for dynamically decorating the DefaultObjectWrapper.wrap(Object) method. In effects this is very similar to extending DefaultObjectWrapper and overriding its DefaultObjectWrapper.wrap(Object), and adding some wrapping logic before and/or after calling super.wrap(obj) (often referred to as decorating). But with this approach instead of subclassing DefaultObjectWrapper and its builder class, you simply list the desired extensions when you build the DefaultObjectWrapper. This is usually more convenient, and more flexible (what extensions you add can be decided on runtime factors) than the subclassing approach.
        Returns:
        An unmodifiable List.

      • setExposeFields

        public void setExposeFields(boolean exposeFields)
        Controls whether public instance fields of classes are exposed to templates.
        Parameters:
        exposeFields - if set to true, public instance fields of classes that do not have a property getter defined can be accessed directly by their name. If there is a property getter for a property of the same name as the field (i.e. getter "getFoo()" and field "foo"), then referring to "foo" in template invokes the getter. If set to false, no access to public instance fields of classes is given. Default is false.
